ce:section.ce:para:
AHNSA is a kind of fluorescent substrate, and its fluorescence intensity varies according to its different response with MnO2 NS and Mn2+. MnO2 NS would inhibit the fluorescence intensity of AHNSA, while Mn2+ has no effect on it and resulted in fluorescence recovery. The presence of OPs will inhibit the activity of AChE, thus preventing the hydrolysis of ATCh to some degree. Due to the decrease in the content of TCh, the reaction of MnO2 NS reduced to Mn2+ is blocked, leading to fluorescence quenching. In these different mixture systems, the fluorescence intensity of AHNSA is different significantly. In Fig. 1
                        (a), (b), (c) and (d), the fluorescent probe AHNSA (35 μM) and the systems with different substances (AChE/ATCh/AChE-ATCh) had similar fluorescence intensity, which showed that both AChE and ATCh have no effect on the fluorescence intensity of AHNSA. In Fig. 1(g) weak fluorescence was observed, which illustrated that MnO2 NS would quench strongly the fluorescence of AHNSA. When MnO2 NS was mixed with the above substances, the fluorescence intensity recovered as shown in Fig. 1(e). It is because that the hydrolysis of ATCh reduces the content of MnO2 NS. However, the presence of PM inhibited enzyme activity and ATCh hydrolysis, and MnO2 NS cannot be reduced to Mn2+. Thus, the fluorescence was quenched again (Fig. 1(f)). Based on the mechanism, we designed a simple fluorescent assay for detection of organophosphorus pesticides with MnO2 NS attaching AChE and ATCh. Moreover, it was found that zeta-potential of MnO2 NS was −13.2 mV, and the zeta-potential of AHNSA was 1.8 mV (Fig. 2
                        ). It was included that AHNSA is bound to MnO2 NS by electrostatic attraction, resulting in fluorescence quenching of AHNSA.
